'''Barbara Ann Underhill''' (born on June 24, 1963 in [[Oshawa, Ontario]], [[Canada]]) is a [[Canadian]] [[pair skater]].  With partner [[Paul Martini]], she is the 1979-1983 [[Canadian Figure Skating Championships|Canadian national champion]], the 1984 [[World Figure Skating Championships|World champion]], and the 1978 [[World Junior Figure Skating Championships|World Junior champion]]. They represented [[Canada at the 1980 Winter Olympics]], where they placed 9th, and [[Canada at the 1984 Winter Olympics|at the 1984 Winter Olympics]], where they placed 7th.

== Post-skating ==
Underhill worked for 16 years as a skating commentator until 2006.<ref name=ic051911>{{cite news | url = http://web.icenetwork.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110519&content_id=19269826&vkey=ice_news | title = Underhill giving hockey players the edge | first = Lois | last = Elfman |date = May 19, 2011 | publisher = IceNetwork | accessdate = June 18, 2011}}</ref> She then began working with hockey players to develop their speed and power, taking advantage of her background in figure skating and also using Dartfish software. She initially worked with the [[Guelph Storm]], of which her husband is a part owner, and then began working with the NHL teams [[New York Rangers]], [[Anaheim Ducks]] and [[Tampa Bay Lightning]].<ref name=ic051911/> Underhill was named in the 2011 edition of [[The Hockey News]]'s list of the 100 most influential people in ice hockey due to her power skating coaching.<ref>The Hockey News, Volume 64, Number 14, January 17, 2011, p.23, Publisher: Caroline Andrews, Transcontinental Media</ref>

Underhill also appeared on [[CBC TV]]'s [[Battle of the Blades]].

== Personal life ==
Underhill married Rick Gaetz, with whom she has two sons, Matthew and Scott, all of whom are involved in hockey.<ref name=ic051911/> She also had twin girls, Sam and Stephanie but lost Stephanie in an accident.<ref>http://www.more.ca/attitude/profiles/barbara-underhill-skating-superstar/a/30120</ref>

